\description{
This function generates one standalone HTML label per species for botanical,
arboretum, and living plant collections. Each label includes taxonomic
information, multilingual species descriptions, browser-based audio playback,
interactive distribution maps, optional personal audio recordings, optional
personal photos, and institutional or package logos.

The function is designed to be used with data generated by \code{arboretum_data()}.
It reads a CSV or Excel file, generates natural-language species descriptions
in the selected built-in languages, creates world and Brazil distribution maps,
and saves the resulting HTML files to an output directory.

In addition to the built-in interface languages (\code{"pt"}, \code{"en"}, \code{"fr"},
and \code{"es"}), users may supply one extra language through \code{add_lang}. This
extra language is intended as a flexible accessibility pathway for situations
where the package interface does not need to be fully translated, but species
labels should still include text and optionally audio in a local, Indigenous,
or community language.

When \code{add_lang} is supplied and the input data contains non-empty values in the
column \code{full_phrases_ADD_LANGUAGE}, the function adds that extra language as an
additional label text option. In this case, the custom language does not pass
through the standard phrase-generation and translation workflow. Instead, the
content is taken directly from \code{full_phrases_ADD_LANGUAGE}.

When personal audio recordings are available in the expected folder structure,
they are embedded in the HTML label and take priority over browser text-to-speech.
If no personal recording is available for a given species and language, the label
falls back to the browser's speech synthesis engine. When personal photos are
available, they are embedded as a slideshow in the species label.
}
\details{
The function follows five main steps:

\enumerate{
\item \strong{Input preparation}
\itemize{
\item Validates the output directory and selected languages.
\item Creates the output directory if it does not exist.
\item Reads the input CSV or Excel file using an internal helper function.
}

\item \strong{Optional media preparation}
\itemize{
\item Checks whether the personal audio directory exists and contains files.
\item Checks whether the photo directory exists and contains files.
\item Copies non-empty personal audio and photo directories into the output
directory and renames the copied folders with a double-underscore prefix.
\item Ignores empty or missing personal audio and photo directories.
}

\item \strong{Phrase generation}
\itemize{
\item Generates species description phrases for each selected built-in language
using internal phrase-generation helpers.
\item When \code{add_lang} is supplied and \code{full_phrases_ADD_LANGUAGE} contains
non-empty text, adds one extra language directly from that column.
\item This extra language bypasses the standard translation and phrase-generation
workflow and is intended for flexible community-based accessibility use cases.
\item Adds plant-use and free-note fields to the visible and spoken text when
language-specific columns are present and not empty.
}

\item \strong{Map generation}
\itemize{
\item Downloads WGSRPD level-3 geographic data for world distribution maps.
\item Reads Brazilian state boundaries using \code{geobr::read_state()}.
\item Creates an interactive world map using native and introduced distribution
information when available.
\item Creates a Brazil map when \code{FFB.stateProvince} contains Brazilian
state records.
}

\item \strong{HTML label generation}
\itemize{
\item Creates one HTML file per species.
\item Adds the species name, authorship, family, description text, audio controls,
language-switching buttons, distribution maps, source/status icons, package
logos, optional custom logo, and optional photo slideshow.
\item Embeds available personal audio files and personal photos as data URIs so
the generated HTML labels are self-contained.
\item Uses browser text-to-speech when personal audio is unavailable.
}
}

Generated file names follow the pattern:

